<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 13 — Inductive Reasoning
  First draft for Part IV.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-inductive-reasoning">

  <title>Inductive Reasoning</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-inductive-reasoning-intro">
    <p>
      Up to this point, we have spent a lot of time with arguments that
      are supposed to be airtight. A valid deductive argument has a kind
      of beautiful stubbornness: if the premises are true, the conclusion
      has to be true. There is no wiggle room, no matter how badly someone
      wants to wiggle.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most of life is not like that. The mechanic hears a sound and thinks
      the alternator is failing. The coach watches practice and predicts
      who will start on Saturday. The doctor looks at a rash, a fever, and
      a lab result, then decides which diagnosis is most likely. The
      evidence can be good. It can be excellent. But it usually does not
      force one conclusion with deductive necessity.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter begins our study of <term>inductive reasoning</term>:
      reasoning in which the premises are intended to make the conclusion
      probable, plausible, or reasonable, without guaranteeing it. That
      shift changes the question. We are no longer asking only, <q>do these premises guarantee the conclusion?</q> We are asking, <q>how much
      support do these premises give this conclusion?</q>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-induction-guarantee-support">
    <title>From Guarantee to Support</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The first step is to stop measuring inductive arguments by the
        wrong standard. If an inductive argument fails to guarantee its
        conclusion, that is not automatically a defect. It was never
        trying to do that job. Another way to put this is that all inductive arguments are invalid, but who cares? 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-deduction-and-induction">
      <title>Two different ambitions</title>
      <p>
        Deductive and inductive arguments have different ambitions.
        A <term>deductive argument</term> aims at guarantee. An
        <term>inductive argument</term> aims at support.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch13-inductive-argument">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An <term>inductive argument</term> is an argument in which
            the premises are intended to make the conclusion probable,
            plausible, or reasonable, but not certain.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Consider a deductive argument:
      </p>
      <p>
        P1: All UMW students are enrolled in a college course.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2: Mina is a UMW student.
      </p>
      <p>
        C: Mina is enrolled in a college course.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the premises are true, the conclusion cannot be false. That is
        the deductive standard.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now consider an inductive argument:
      </p>
      <p>
        P1: The last six times the 7:40 train was delayed, the delay was
        caused by signal problems near Union Station.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2: The 7:40 train is delayed again this morning.
      </p>
      <p>
        C: The delay is probably caused by signal problems near Union
        Station.
      </p>
      <p>
        The conclusion might be false even if both premises are true. Maybe
        there is a power outage. Maybe a tree fell on the tracks. Maybe the
        signal problems finally got fixed and a new problem showed up. But
        the premises still give us a reason to think the conclusion is
        likely. That is the inductive standard.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-induction-not-lesser">
      <title>Inductive does not mean sloppy</title>
      <p>
        It is tempting to hear <q>not guaranteed</q> as <q>not serious.</q>
        Resist that temptation. Inductive reasoning is not failed
        deduction. It is a different kind of reasoning, with different
        standards.
      </p>
      <p>
        A weather forecast can be excellent even if rain does not arrive.
        A medical diagnosis can be responsible even if later evidence
        overturns it. A scientific theory can be well supported even though
        future research might revise it. In all of these cases, the
        important question is not whether the evidence makes error
        impossible. The important question is whether the evidence makes
        the conclusion reasonable.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-ch13-rain-forecast">
      <title>A forecast is not a proof</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the forecast says there is an 80 percent chance of rain
          this afternoon. Dark clouds are moving in, the humidity is high,
          and radar shows a storm line to the west. You conclude that you
          should bring an umbrella.
        </p>
        <p>
          That reasoning is not deductively valid. You might carry the
          umbrella all day and never open it. Still, the reasoning is good.
          The evidence raises the probability of rain enough to make the
          conclusion practical.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-inductive-strength">
    <title>Inductive Strength</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Since inductive arguments do not aim at validity, we need a
        different evaluative vocabulary. The central term is
        <term>strength</term>.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch13-strong-inductive-argument">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>strong inductive argument</term> is an inductive
          argument whose premises, if true, make its conclusion highly
          probable.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch13-weak-inductive-argument">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>weak inductive argument</term> is an inductive argument
          whose premises, even if true, do not make its conclusion very
          probable.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Here is a strong inductive argument:
    </p>
    <p>
      P1: Every section of this course taught in the last five years has
      required a final exam.
    </p>
    <p>
      P2: This semester's section is taught by the same department, using
      the same course requirements.
    </p>
    <p>
      C: This semester's section will probably require a final exam.
    </p>
    <p>
      The conclusion is not guaranteed. The department could change its
      policy. The instructor could try something new. But the premises
      provide substantial support.
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a weak inductive argument:
    </p>
    <p>
      P1: The first person I saw walking out of the library today was
      carrying a coffee.
    </p>
    <p>
      C: Most people who use the library carry coffee.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is not much to go on. The premise may be true, but one person
      leaving one building at one moment does not tell us much about most
      library users.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cogency">
      <title>Strength and truth</title>
      <p>
        The distinction between strong and weak arguments concerns the
        support relation: if the premises were true, how much support
        would they give the conclusion? That means strength is like
        validity in one important respect: it is not the same thing as
        having true premises.
      </p>
      <p>
        For inductive arguments, the rough analogue of soundness is
        <term>cogency</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch13-cogent-argument">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>cogent argument</term> is a strong inductive argument
            with true premises.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        A strong argument with false premises is not cogent. A weak
        argument with true premises is not cogent either. A cogent
        argument needs both pieces: good support and true starting points.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-defeasible">
      <title>Inductive arguments can be defeated</title>
      <p>
        Inductive support is <term>defeasible</term>. That means new
        information can weaken or overturn it without showing that the
        original reasoning was deductively invalid. This is one reason
        inductive reasoning feels so ordinary. We update all the time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose the 7:40 train is delayed and past delays point toward
        signal problems. Then a station announcement says, <q>All trains
        are delayed because of a medical emergency.</q> The earlier
        inference was reasonable before the announcement. After the
        announcement, it is no longer reasonable. The evidence changed,
        so the best conclusion changed with it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-13-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Track a live inductive inference</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For one day, watch for a real-life conclusion you draw without
          certainty. It can be ordinary: whether to bring an umbrella,
          whether a dining hall line will move quickly, whether a team is
          likely to win, whether a news claim is probably accurate, or
          whether a friend is upset from the way they texted.
        </p>
        <p>
          Write down:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>the conclusion you drew;</p></li>
          <li><p>the evidence you used;</p></li>
          <li><p>whether the inference was strong, moderate, or weak;</p></li>
          <li><p>one piece of information that would strengthen it;</p></li>
          <li><p>one piece of information that would weaken it.</p></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The point is not to find a dramatic case. The point is to notice
          how often we reason responsibly without proof.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-generalization-samples">
    <title>Generalizing from Samples</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        One common form of inductive reasoning moves from observed cases
        to a broader conclusion. We look at some members of a group and
        draw a conclusion about the group as a whole.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch13-inductive-generalization">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>inductive generalization</term> is an argument that
          draws a conclusion about a larger population from observations
          of a sample.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch13-sample-population">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>sample</term> is the group actually observed. The
          <term>population</term> is the larger group the argument draws
          a conclusion about.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Here is the basic pattern:
    </p>
    <p>
      P1: The observed members of group G have feature F.
    </p>
    <p>
      C: Most, many, or some specified proportion of all members of group
      G probably have feature F.
    </p>
    <p>
      This pattern is everywhere. Course evaluations, polls, product
      reviews, medical studies, political surveys, and campus rumors all
      rely on some version of it. Sometimes the reasoning is careful.
      Sometimes it is a mess wearing a nice jacket.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-sample-size">
      <title>Sample size matters</title>
      <p>
        Other things being equal, larger samples usually provide better
        support than smaller samples. If you ask two students whether the
        new registration system works well, you have learned something,
        but not much. If you ask two hundred students from different years,
        majors, and registration times, you have learned more.
      </p>
      <p>
        Larger samples are not magic. A large bad sample can still mislead
        us. But tiny samples are especially dangerous because they make
        accident look like pattern.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-representative-samples">
      <title>Representativeness matters more</title>
      <p>
        A sample also needs to be <term>representative</term>. A
        representative sample resembles the population in the respects
        that matter for the question being asked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose you want to know whether UMW students support extending
        library hours during finals. If you survey only students who are
        already inside the library at 11:45 p.m., you may get a very clear
        answer, but your sample is tilted. Those students are exactly the
        people most likely to want later hours. Their answers matter, but
        they may not represent the whole student body.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch13-biased-sample">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>biased sample</term> is a sample that differs from
            the target population in a way that is likely to distort the
            conclusion.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ch13-hasty-generalization">
      <title>Hasty generalization</title>
      <p>
        A <term>hasty generalization</term> occurs when someone draws a
        broad conclusion from too little evidence or from an unrepresentative
        sample.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>Two people in my discussion section hated the reading, so
        nobody liked it</q> is a hasty generalization. Maybe the whole
        class hated it. That is possible. But two irritated classmates are
        not enough evidence to support a conclusion about everyone.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that the problem is not that the conclusion must be false.
        It might be true. The problem is that the evidence does not yet
        earn it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-causal-reasoning">
    <title>Causal Reasoning</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Another central form of inductive reasoning tries to identify
        causes. We see one thing happen, then another, and we ask whether
        the first helped bring about the second.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-ch13-causal-argument">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>causal argument</term> is an argument whose conclusion
          claims that one event, condition, or factor causes or contributes
          to another.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Causal reasoning is powerful because causes matter. If a tutoring
      program improves pass rates, we may want to expand it. If a drug
      causes harmful side effects, we may want to restrict it. If a
      policy reduces crashes, we may want to keep it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Causal reasoning is also hard because the world does not politely
      isolate one variable at a time. Lots of things change together.
    </p>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-correlation">
      <title>Correlation is not causation</title>
      <p>
        A <term>correlation</term> is an association between two things:
        as one changes, the other tends to change too. Correlations can
        be important evidence. But a correlation by itself does not prove
        causation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose students who attend optional review sessions tend to earn
        higher exam scores. That correlation is real evidence, but it does
        not settle the causal question by itself. Maybe the review sessions
        improve exam scores. Maybe students who were already more motivated
        are more likely to attend review sessions and also more likely to
        study. Maybe both are happening.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-alternative-causes">
      <title>Ruling out alternatives</title>
      <p>
        Good causal reasoning asks what else might explain the pattern.
        Three alternatives are especially common.
      </p>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Reverse causation</title>
          <p>
            Maybe B causes A rather than A causing B. People with better
            grades might attend review sessions because they are already
            more engaged.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Common cause</title>
          <p>
            Maybe a third factor causes both A and B. Motivation might
            cause both review attendance and higher scores.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Coincidence</title>
          <p>
            Maybe the pattern is a fluke, especially if the sample is
            small or the comparison was chosen after looking at the data.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
      <p>
        Causal reasoning improves when we design observations or
        experiments that reduce these alternatives. That is one reason
        controlled studies matter.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example xml:id="ex-ch13-sleep-grades">
      <title>Sleep and grades</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose a campus health survey finds that students who sleep at
          least seven hours a night have higher average grades than students
          who sleep less than seven hours. It is tempting to conclude that
          sleeping more causes better grades.
        </p>
        <p>
          That conclusion may be right. But the survey alone leaves open
          other possibilities. Students with less stressful schedules might
          both sleep more and study more effectively. Students with strong
          time-management skills might both protect their sleep and keep up
          with coursework. The survey gives us a place to start, not a
          deductive proof.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-analogy-explanation">
    <title>Analogy and Best Explanation</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Not all induction moves from samples to populations or from
        correlations to causes. Two other common patterns are arguments
        by analogy and inferences to the best explanation.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-analogy">
      <title>Arguments by analogy</title>
      <p>
        An <term>argument by analogy</term> reasons from similarities
        between two things. The basic thought is simple: these things are
        alike in certain known respects, so they are probably alike in
        some further respect.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch13-argument-by-analogy">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An <term>argument by analogy</term> is an inductive argument
            that concludes that because two things are similar in some
            respects, they are probably similar in another respect.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Suppose two courses are taught by the same instructor, use the
        same textbook, assign the same kinds of quizzes, and have the same
        exam format. A student who did well in the first course might infer
        that the same study strategy will probably work in the second.
        That is analogical reasoning.
      </p>
      <p>
        The strength of an analogy depends on the relevance of the
        similarities. If the two courses only meet in the same building,
        the analogy is weak. If they share the same instructor, assignments,
        grading style, and exam format, the analogy is stronger.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-best-explanation">
      <title>Inference to the best explanation</title>
      <p>
        Sometimes we have a set of facts and several possible explanations.
        We reason toward the explanation that would make the facts least
        surprising. This is often called <term>inference to the best
        explanation</term>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-ch13-best-explanation">
        <statement>
          <p>
            An <term>inference to the best explanation</term> is an
            inductive argument that treats a hypothesis as likely because
            it would best explain the available evidence.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        You walk into a classroom and see wet umbrellas by the door,
        students shaking water from their sleeves, and dark clouds through
        the window. The best explanation is that it is raining. You have
        not proven rain deductively. A sprinkler accident is possible.
        A film crew with prop umbrellas is possible. But the rain
        explanation is simpler, more natural, and fits the evidence better.
      </p>
      <p>
        Good explanatory reasoning compares alternatives. It asks: which
        explanation fits the evidence? Which explains more of it? Which
        requires the fewest extra assumptions? Which survives when we look
        for counterevidence?
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-induction-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      Inductive reasoning is the broad category. Probability gives us a
      way to talk more precisely about degrees of support. Instead of
      saying only that a conclusion is likely, unlikely, strong, weak, or
      plausible, probability lets us ask how likely it is and how new
      evidence should change our confidence.
    </p>
    <p>
      The next chapter begins that work. We will not treat probability as
      a bag of formulas to memorize. We will treat it as a way of thinking
      carefully about uncertainty, evidence, and change of mind.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch13">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced inductive reasoning. The core ideas, section
      by section:
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>From Guarantee to Support (§13.1).</alert> Deductive
      arguments aim at guarantee. Inductive arguments aim at support.
      An inductive argument can be good even though its premises do not
      make its conclusion certain.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Inductive Strength (§13.2).</alert> Inductive arguments are
      evaluated as strong or weak. A strong inductive argument has premises
      that, if true, make the conclusion highly probable. A cogent argument
      is strong and has true premises. Inductive support is defeasible:
      new evidence can weaken or overturn it.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Generalizing from Samples (§13.3).</alert> Inductive
      generalizations move from observations about a sample to conclusions
      about a population. Good samples are large enough and representative.
      Bad generalizations often rely on samples that are too small or
      biased.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Causal Reasoning (§13.4).</alert> Causal arguments claim
      that one factor causes or contributes to another. Correlation can be
      evidence for causation, but it is not enough by itself. Good causal
      reasoning considers reverse causation, common causes, coincidence,
      and other alternatives.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Analogy and Best Explanation (§13.5).</alert> Arguments by
      analogy reason from relevant similarities. Inferences to the best
      explanation treat a hypothesis as likely because it explains the
      available evidence better than its competitors.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§13.6).</alert> Probability gives us a
      more precise vocabulary for degrees of support and changing
      confidence in light of evidence.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch13-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-argument-by-analogy">
        <title>Argument by analogy</title>
        <p>An inductive argument that concludes that because two things are similar in some respects, they are probably similar in another respect. (§13.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-biased-sample">
        <title>Biased sample</title>
        <p>A sample that differs from the target population in a way that is likely to distort the conclusion. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-causal-argument">
        <title>Causal argument</title>
        <p>An argument whose conclusion claims that one event, condition, or factor causes or contributes to another. (§13.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-cogent-argument">
        <title>Cogent argument</title>
        <p>A strong inductive argument with true premises. (§13.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-correlation">
        <title>Correlation</title>
        <p>An association between two things, where changes in one tend to be connected with changes in the other. (§13.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-defeasible">
        <title>Defeasible</title>
        <p>Capable of being weakened or overturned by new evidence. Inductive support is defeasible. (§13.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-hasty-generalization">
        <title>Hasty generalization</title>
        <p>An inductive generalization drawn from too little evidence or from an unrepresentative sample. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-inductive-argument">
        <title>Inductive argument</title>
        <p>An argument in which the premises are intended to make the conclusion probable, plausible, or reasonable, but not certain. (§13.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-inductive-generalization">
        <title>Inductive generalization</title>
        <p>An argument that draws a conclusion about a larger population from observations of a sample. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-inference-best-explanation">
        <title>Inference to the best explanation</title>
        <p>An inductive argument that treats a hypothesis as likely because it would best explain the available evidence. (§13.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-population">
        <title>Population</title>
        <p>The larger group an inductive generalization draws a conclusion about. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-representative-sample">
        <title>Representative sample</title>
        <p>A sample that resembles the target population in the respects that matter for the question being asked. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-sample">
        <title>Sample</title>
        <p>The group actually observed in an inductive generalization. (§13.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-strong-inductive-argument">
        <title>Strong inductive argument</title>
        <p>An inductive argument whose premises, if true, make its conclusion highly probable. (§13.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch13-weak-inductive-argument">
        <title>Weak inductive argument</title>
        <p>An inductive argument whose premises, even if true, do not make its conclusion very probable. (§13.2)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch13">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Deductive or Inductive?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each argument, say whether it is best understood as
          deductive or inductive. Then briefly explain your answer.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>All biology majors must complete a lab science requirement. Ana is a biology major. Therefore, Ana must complete a lab science requirement.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The last four buses on this route arrived late during heavy rain. It is raining heavily now. So this bus will probably arrive late.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>If the server is down, the login page will not load. The server is down. Therefore, the login page will not load.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>Most students who submitted the practice quiz earned higher scores on the exam. Jordan submitted the practice quiz. So Jordan probably earned a higher score on the exam.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>No committee members voted against the proposal. Lee is a committee member. Therefore, Lee did not vote against the proposal.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p>The restaurant has hundreds of recent reviews, and nearly all mention slow service. So service at the restaurant is probably slow.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Strong or Weak?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each inductive argument, say whether it is strong, moderate,
          or weak. Identify the feature of the evidence that matters most.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>I asked one person in the dining hall whether the new meal plan is popular. They said no. So the new meal plan is unpopular with students.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>A random survey of 850 students found that 71 percent support extending library hours during finals. So most students probably support extending library hours during finals.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The last three assignments in this course were due on Sunday night. So the next assignment will probably be due on Sunday night.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>Every charger I have borrowed from this brand has broken within two months, and I have borrowed six of them. So the next charger from this brand will probably break quickly.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>The first five people who commented on the article were angry. So everyone who read the article was angry.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Samples and Generalizations</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each case, identify the sample, the population, and one
          possible problem with the generalization.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>A student asks ten friends in her residence hall whether first-year parking should be expanded. Nine say yes. She concludes that UMW students strongly support expanding first-year parking.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>A campus office emails a survey to every student and receives 1,200 responses from students across all class years. Most respondents say they use the tutoring center at least once a semester. The office concludes that tutoring-center use is common among UMW students.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>A podcast host reads five negative comments about a new movie and concludes that audiences hate it.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <p>A professor surveys only students who attended an optional exam review and concludes that almost everyone in the class found the review helpful.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Causal Reasoning</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each causal claim, identify at least one alternative
          explanation that should be considered.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Students who sit near the front of the classroom tend to earn higher grades. Therefore, sitting near the front causes higher grades.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>People who use a budgeting app save more money than people who do not. Therefore, the app causes people to save more money.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>After the city added bike lanes downtown, reported bike accidents decreased. Therefore, the bike lanes caused the decrease.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>A study finds that people who eat breakfast regularly have higher average energy levels. Therefore, eating breakfast causes higher energy levels.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Analogy and Explanation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each item, identify whether the reasoning is mainly an
          argument by analogy or an inference to the best explanation.
          Then briefly evaluate it.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>This course uses the same textbook, quiz format, and instructor as the course I took last semester. My old study schedule worked well there, so it will probably work well here too.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The sidewalk is wet, students are carrying umbrellas, and thunder is audible outside. The best explanation is that it is raining.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The two phones are the same color and size. My phone has excellent battery life, so that phone probably has excellent battery life too.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p>The office door is locked, the lights are off, and nobody answered three knocks. The professor is probably not in the office.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch13-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 13-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch13-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the inductive inference you tracked in Field
            Exercise 13-1. Reconstruct it in standard form. Then explain
            whether you now think the inference was strong, moderate, or
            weak. What evidence would have made you more confident? What
            evidence would have made you change your mind?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
